# Accessing Disk

The `System.IO` namespace provides all the tools you need.

## The `File` Class
Provides static methods for checking, creating, copying, deleting, accessing, and opening files.

```csharp
using System.IO;

if (File.Exists("data.txt")) {
    Console.WriteLine("Found it!");
}
```

# Quick Methods ⚡

For small text files, use helper methods:

```csharp
string content = "Hello File!";

// Write (Overwrites)
File.WriteAllText("test.txt", content);

// Append
File.AppendAllText("test.txt", "\nNew Line");

// Read
string readText = File.ReadAllText("test.txt");
Console.WriteLine(readText);
```

# Path.Combine 🛣️

Windows uses `\`, Linux/Mac uses `/`.
Hardcoding paths like `"C:\folder\file"` breaks cross-platform compatibility.

Use `Path.Combine()`:
```csharp
string folder = "MyData";
string file = "info.txt";

// Automatically uses correct separator
string fullPath = Path.Combine(folder, file); 
```

# For Large Files 🌊

Reading/Writing everything at once uses a lot of RAM. Use Streams for efficiency.

```csharp
// Writing
using (StreamWriter sw = new StreamWriter("log.txt")) {
    sw.WriteLine("Log Entry 1");
}

// Reading line by line
using (StreamReader sr = new StreamReader("log.txt")) {
    string line;
    while ((line = sr.ReadLine()) != null) {
        Console.WriteLine(line);
    }
}
```

# Saving Objects 💾

Modern apps allow saving objects to JSON strings.

```csharp
using System.Text.Json;

Person p = new Person { Name = "Alice", Age = 25 };

// Serialize (Object -> String)
string json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(p);
File.WriteAllText("person.json", json);

// Deserialize (String -> Object)
Person p2 = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<Person>(json);
```

